# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: is-is-routing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] Convergence is an important notion for a set of routers that engage in dynamic routing.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] All interior gateway protocols rely on convergence to function properly.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] "To have, or be, converged" is the normal state of an operational autonomous system.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] The Exterior Gateway Routing Protocol BGP typically never converges because the Internet is too big for changes to be communicated fast enough.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] When a routing protocol process is enabled, every participating router will attempt to exchange information about the topology of the network.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] The extent of this information exchange, the way it is sent and received, and the type of information required vary widely depending on the routing protocol in use, see e.g.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] A state of convergence is achieved once all routing protocol-specific information has been distributed to all routers participating in the routing protocol process.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] Any change in the network that affects routing tables will break the convergence temporarily until this change has been successfully communicated to all other routers.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] RIP is a routing protocol that converges so slowly that even a network of a few routers can take a couple of minutes to converge.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] In case of a new route being advertised, triggered updates can speed up RIP's convergence but to flush a route that previously existed takes longer due to the holddown timers in use.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] OSPF is an example of a fast-converging routing protocol.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] A network of a few OSPF routers can converge in a matter of seconds.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] Certain configuration and hardware conditions will prevent a network from ever converging.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] For instance, a "flapping" interface (an interface that frequently changes its state between "up" and "down") might cause conflicting information to propagate throughout the network so the routers never agree on its current state.
[src:is-is-routing/convergence-routing] Under certain circumstances it might be desirable to withhold detailed routing information from parts of the network via route aggregation, thereby speeding up convergence of the topological information shared by all routers.
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] An **interior gateway protocol** (**IGP**) or **interior routing protocol** is a type of routing protocol used for exchanging routing table information between gateways (commonly routers) *within* an autonomous system (for example, a system of corporate local area networks).
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] This routing information can then be used to route network-layer protocols like IP.
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Interior gateway protocols can be divided into two categories: distance-vector routing protocols and link-state routing protocols.
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Specific examples of IGPs include Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] By contrast, exterior gateway protocols are used to exchange routing information *between* autonomous systems and rely on IGPs to resolve routes within an autonomous system.
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Advanced distance vector routing protocols have both the features of distance vector routing protocols and link-state routing protocols.
[src:is-is-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] One example is Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The IS-IS protocol is defined in ISO/IEC 10589:2002 as an international standard within the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) reference design.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS is an interior gateway protocol, designed for use within an administrative domain or network.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This is in contrast to exterior gateway protocols, primarily Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), which is used for routing between autonomous systems.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS is a link-state routing protocol, operating by flooding link state information throughout a network of routers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Each IS-IS router builds its own link-state database (LSDB) by collecting the flooded link-state information from other routers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Like OSPF, IS-IS uses Dijkstra's algorithm for computing the best path through the network.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Packets (datagrams) are then forwarded along the computed shortest paths to their destinations.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS was developed by Digital Equipment Corporation as part of DECnet Phase V.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published an IS-IS specification in 1990, but that RFC was later retracted and marked as *historic* because it republished a draft rather than a final version of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) standard, causing confusion.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The protocol was standardised by ISO in 1992 as ISO 10589 for use between Intermediate Systems rather than end systems or hosts.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The purpose of IS-IS was to make the routing of datagrams possible using the ISO-developed OSI protocol stack called Connectionless-mode Network Service (CLNS).
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS was developed at roughly the same time that the Internet Engineering Task Force IETF was developing a similar protocol called OSPF.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS was later extended to support routing of *datagrams* in the Internet Protocol (IP), the network-layer protocol of the global Internet.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This extension is known as *Integrated IS-IS*.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] By 2005, IS-IS had become the de facto standard for large service provider network backbones.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The ISO IS-IS standard defines its own terminology for network components, some of which differs from the terms usually found in the industry.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS operates over both broadcast (LAN) and point-to-point network links.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Adjacencies are formed between neighboring routers to exchange routing information.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS Hello PDUs are exchanged periodically to establish and maintain adjacencies.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] On broadcast networks, a Designated Intermediate System (DIS) is elected based on interface priority and system ID.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This hello packet will be sent separately for Level 1 or Level 2.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] There are three IS-IS hello packets depending on the circuit type.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This contains the actual routing information.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] If the Pseudonode ID is equal to zero, then it represents a real intermediate system.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Any non-zero value means that the LSP is generated by a DIS (Pseudonode).
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] If an LSP exceeds the maximum transmission unit (MTU), it is fragmented into multiple LSPs distinguished by a Fragment ID.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Fragment numbering begins at zero; an unfragmented LSP consists of a single fragment (ID 0), while additional fragments are assigned incrementing identifiers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The Complete Sequence Number PDU (CSNP) is sent by the Designated Intermediate System (DIS) at regular intervals, typically every 10 seconds.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] It contains a summary of Link State PDUs (LSPs), including sequence numbers and checksums.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] If a router detects discrepancies between its link-state database and a received CSNP, it sends a PSNP requesting the missing or updated LSPs.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Unlike most IP routing protocols, IS-IS operates directly over Layer 2 rather than relying on Layer 3 for transport, and does not use IP addresses to identify interfaces.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Instead, IS-IS identifies interfaces using Layer 2 addresses (SNPA, e.g.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] MAC addresses on Ethernet), and identifies routing nodes using ISO network addresses.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Each Intermediate System is assigned a Network Entity Title (NET), which is an NSAP address used to identify the router within the IS-IS routing domain.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] A NET is an NSAP used as a Network Entity Title where the NSEL field is set to zero.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] While not required by the protocol, a common operational practice is to set the System ID field to a unique IPv4 address from one of the router’s loopback interfaces.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] On a single intermediate system there can be up to 3 NET addresses.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This may be useful during migration of an IS from one area to another.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The NET consists of an *Area*, *System ID* and *NSEL* field.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] *Area* itself consists of an *AFI* (*Address Family Identifier*) and an *Area ID*.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Area can have a variable length of 1–13 bytes.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The System ID is six bytes long and the NSEL is one byte.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] When administering large networks, using IP addresses directly can be inconvenient.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] In large networks, routers are often identified using hostnames such as "if-bundle-22-2.qcore1.pye-paris.as6453.net", which may encode location and topology information.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] In many routing protocols, routers are identified by IP addresses and hostnames are resolved externally using DNS.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Because IS-IS operates directly over the data link layer rather than over IP, hostname mappings can be distributed within the protocol itself.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS link-state PDUs may include **Type-Length-Value 137** (TLV 137), which advertises a hostname associated with an IS-IS System ID derived from the router's NET.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Similar to OSPF, IS-IS employs the concept of areas to divide the network, reducing the overall burden on routers in the network, by only requiring them to have complete link-state information for their area.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] In IS-IS, ISs operate at Level 1, Level 2 or Level 1/Level 2.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] When a Level 1 router needs to send traffic to a destination not within its area, it directs it to a Level 1/Level 2 router.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Level 1/Level 2 routers advertise their status as boundary routers by setting the Attached Bit (ATT), in its Level 1 LSP.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Routers that receive this LSP will add a default route to the origin of the LSP.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] External routes may be redistributed into Level 1 areas via Level 1/Level 2 routers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] By default, external routes are not advertised into the Level 2 backbone; redistribution into Level 2 must be explicitly configured on Level 1/Level 2 routers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS LSPs contain information about the LSP itself in the attribute block of the LSP header, which is 8 bits long.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] When IS-IS was initially introduced, the default type–length–value (TLV) formats for IS reachability (TLV 2) and IP reachability (TLVs 128 and 130) used a 6-bit link metric field with a maximum value of 63 and a 10-bit path metric field with a maximum value of 1023.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] As network scale and link speeds increased, these metric limitations became restrictive for larger topologies.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] To address this, new TLVs were introduced: TLV 22 for extended IS reachability and TLV 135 for extended IP reachability.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] These extensions increase the supported link metric to 24 bits (maximum value 16,777,215) and the path metric to 32 bits (maximum value 4,294,967,295).
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Metrics without TLV 22 and 135 are called *narrow*, and metrics that include them are called *wide*.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Wide and narrow metrics may be configured independently on a per-level basis.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Compared to OSPF, IS-IS adjacency formation rules are simpler and depend primarily on the router's level.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Level 1 adjacencies require matching area addresses, whereas Level 2 adjacencies are formed independently of area membership.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Similar to OSPF, all routers in a broadcast domain need to form adjacencies and exchange LSPs, resulting in there being $n^{2}$ LSPs for each router in the domain.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] In order to overcome this issue, on each LAN segment a designated intermediate system (DIS) is elected.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The router with the highest priority and System ID is elected as the DIS, but if another router is connected with a higher priority (or higher System ID if the priorities are equal), will be elected as the new DIS.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Instead of each router forming an adjacency with every other router in the broadcast domain, each router forms an adjacency with just the DIS, and the DIS becomes responsible for relaying LSPs to the subordinate routers, in a hub-and-spoke topology.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] An elected DIS router is a pseudonode, which uses the resources (including System ID) of one real router.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The Pseudonode ID in LSPs originated by a DIS, always have a non-zero Pseudonode ID field.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] The DIS will send periodic CSNPs on the LAN segment and reply to PSNPs from other routers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] If the DIS stops communicating, a new DIS will be elected in the segment.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS supports authentication of Protocol Data Units (PDUs), including IIH (IS-IS Hello), Link State PDUs (LSPs), and Sequence Number PDUs (SNPs).
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Authentication may be configured on a per-interface and per-level (Level 1 or Level 2) basis.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Authentication mechanisms include simple password authentication and cryptographic authentication using HMAC-MD5, as well as HMAC-SHA variants.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] To mitigate replay attacks, IS-IS uses sequence numbers in IIH PDUs during adjacency establishment, ensuring that stale or duplicate messages are not accepted.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Unlike OSPF, which operates at Layer 3, IS-IS encapsulates its PDUs into Layer 2 frames, and does not depend on Layer 3 protocols, such as IPv4 or IPv6.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] To support IPv6 routing information, TLV 232 for *IPv6 interface address* and TLV 236 for *IPv6 reachability* were added.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] To display supported Layer 3 protocols, also called *NLPID* (*Network Layer Protocol ID*), TLV 129 is used.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Here, IPv4 has code of *0xCC*, while IPv6 has a code of *0x8E*.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] There might be an issue if the IPv4 and IPv6 topologies do not overlap.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This could happen due to misconfiguration or lack of support for IPv6 by routers in the network.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] For this situations, multi-topology support is added to IS-IS.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] TLV 229 was added to indicate *support for multi-topologies*, such as IPv4 unicast and IPv6 unicast.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] If multi-topology is enabled, IS-IS will calculate separate SPF tree for IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] This means twice the resource usage, but from the other side, this prevents traffic black holes.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] When multi-topology is enabled, then IS-IS will use TLV 222 for *Multi-topology IS* *reachability*, TLV 235 for *Multi-topology IP reachability* and TLV 236 for *Multi-topology IPv6 reachability*.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Depending on the configuration, the router can have Level 1, Level 2 or both Level 1/Level 2 Link-State Databases.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS uses Dijkstra's algorithm to generate the routing tables from these databases.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] But there can be situations, when IS-IS router has exactly the same prefix in different level databases, or external and internal.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS uses Hello packets (IIH) to share information about routers and to establish adjacencies.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Hello packets also help detect faults between neighboring routers.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] Fault detection can be sped up by lowering the hello packet transmission intervals, but this increases CPU load.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] BFD is a low-overhead fault detection protocol that operates independently of the routing protocol and can provide sub-second detection with minimal impact on the CPU.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] IS-IS is the base for the control plane in Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] SPB enables equal-cost multipath routing among Ethernet switches in a mesh topology: Ethernet frames are forwarded along multiple load-balanced, service-specific paths, which are all equally the shortest.
[src:is-is-routing/is-is] To support this, SPB extends IS-IS with new TLVs.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The link-state protocol is performed by every *switching node* in the network (i.e., nodes which are prepared to forward packets; in the Internet, these are called routers).
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The basic concept of link-state routing is that every node constructs a *map* of the connectivity to the network in the form of a graph, showing which nodes are connected to which other nodes.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each node then independently calculates the next best logical *path* from it to every possible destination in the network.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each collection of best paths will then form each node's routing table.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This contrasts with distance-vector routing protocols, which work by having each node share its routing table with its neighbors.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In a link-state protocol, the only information passed between nodes is *connectivity related*.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In link-state routing protocols, each router possesses information about the complete network topology.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each router then independently calculates the best next hop from it for every possible destination in the network using local information of the topology.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The collection of best next hops forms the routing table.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This contrasts with distance-vector routing protocols, which work by having each node share its routing table with its neighbours.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In a link-state protocol, the only information passed between the nodes is the information used to construct the connectivity maps.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] What is believed to be the first adaptive routing network of computers, using link-state routing, was designed and implemented during 1976–1977 by a team from Plessey Radar led by Bernard J Harris; the project was for "Wavell" – a system of computer command and control for the British Army.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The first link-state routing concept was published in 1979 by John M.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] McQuillan (then at Bolt, Beranek and Newman) as a mechanism that would calculate routes more quickly when network conditions changed and thus lead to more stable routing.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The technique was later adapted for use in the contemporary link-state routing protocols IS-IS and OSPF.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Cisco literature refers to Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) as a "hybrid" protocol, despite the fact it distributes routing tables instead of topology maps.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] However, it does synchronize routing tables at start-up as OSPF does and sends specific updates only when topology changes occur.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In 2004, Radia Perlman proposed using link-state routing for layer 2 frame forwarding with devices called routing bridges, or Rbridges.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force has standardized the Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links (TRILL) protocol to accomplish this.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] More recently, this hierarchical technique was applied to wireless mesh networks using the Optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Where a connection can have varying quality, the quality of a connection can be used to select better connections.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This is used in some ad hoc routing protocols that use radio frequency transmission.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The first main stage in the link-state algorithm is to give a map of the network to every node.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This is done with several subsidiary steps.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] First, each node needs to determine what other ports it is connected to over fully working links; it does this using *reachability protocol* that it runs periodically and separately with each of its directly connected neighbours.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This message is sent to all the nodes on a network.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] As a necessary precursor, each node in the network remembers, for every one of *its* neighbors, the sequence number of the last link-state message which it received from that node.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This procedure rapidly gets a copy of the latest version of each node's link-state advertisement to every node in the network.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The complete set produces the graph for the map of the network.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The link-state message giving information about the neighbors is recomputed and then flooded throughout the network whenever there is a change in the connectivity between the node and its neighbors, e.g., when a link fails.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The second main stage in the link-state algorithm is to produce routing tables by inspecting the maps.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each node independently runs an algorithm over the map to determine the shortest path from itself to every other node in the network; generally, some variant of Dijkstra's algorithm is used.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] A node maintains two data structures: a Tree data structure tree containing nodes which are "done", and a list of *candidates*.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The algorithm starts with both structures empty; it then adds to the first one the node itself.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The two steps are repeated as long as there are any nodes left in the candidate list.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] (When there are none, all the nodes in the network will have been added to the tree.) This procedure ends with the tree containing all the nodes in the network.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] For any given destination node, the best path for that destination is the node which is the first step from the root node, down the branch in the shortest-path tree which leads toward the desired destination node.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Whenever a change in the connectivity map happens, it is necessary to recompute the shortest-path tree and then recreate the routing table.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] BBN Technologies discovered how to compute only that part of the tree which could have been affected by a given change in the map.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In some cases, it is reasonable to reduce the number of nodes that generate LSA messages.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] For this reason, a topology reduction strategy can be applied, in which only a subset of the network nodes generate LSA messages.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Two widely studied approaches for topology reduction are multipoint relays that are at the base of the Optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR) but have also been proposed for OSPF and connected dominating sets that were again proposed for OSPF.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] With Fisheye State Routing (FSR), the LSA are sent with different time-to-live values to restrict their diffusion and limit the overhead due to control messages.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The same concept is used also in the Hazy Sighted Link State Routing Protocol.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] If all the nodes are not working from exactly the same map, *routing loops* can form.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] These are situations in which, in the simplest form, two neighboring nodes each think the other is the best path to a given destination.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Any packet headed to that destination arriving at either node will loop between the two, hence the name.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Routing loops involving more than two nodes are also possible.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This can occur since each node computes its shortest-path tree and its routing table without interacting in any way with any other nodes.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] If two nodes start with different maps, it is possible to have scenarios in which routing loops are created.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In certain circumstances, differential loops may be enabled within a multi-cloud environment.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Variable access nodes across the interface protocol may also bypass the simultaneous access node problem.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The Optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR) is a link-state routing protocol optimized for mobile ad hoc networks (which can also be used on other wireless ad hoc networks).
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] OLSR is proactive and uses hello and topology control messages to disseminate link-state information into the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Using hello messages, each node discovers two-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] MPRs make OLSR distinct from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:is-is-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Individual nodes use the topology information to compute next-hop paths regarding all nodes in the network using shortest-hop forwarding paths.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF gathers link state information from available routers and constructs a topology map of the network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The topology is presented as a routing table to the internet layer for routing packets by their destination IP address.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF supports Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) networks and is widely used in large enterprise networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] IS-IS, another LSR-based protocol, is more common in large service provider networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Originally designed in the 1980s, OSPF version 2 is defined in RFC 2328 (1998).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The updates for IPv6 are specified as OSPF version 3 in RFC 5340 (2008).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF supports the Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) addressing model.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF is an interior gateway protocol (IGP) for routing Internet Protocol (IP) packets within a single routing domain, such as an autonomous system.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It gathers link state information from available routers and constructs a topology map of the network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The topology is presented as a routing table to the internet layer, which routes packets based solely on their destination IP address.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF detects changes in the topology, such as link failures, and converges on a new loop-free routing structure within seconds.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It computes the shortest-path tree for each route using a method based on Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The OSPF routing policies for constructing a route table are governed by link metrics associated with each routing interface.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Cost factors may be the distance of a router (round-trip time), data throughput of a link, or link availability and reliability, expressed as simple unitless numbers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This provides a dynamic process of traffic load balancing between routes of equal cost.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF divides the network into routing *areas* to simplify administration and optimize traffic and resource utilization.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Areas are identified by 32-bit numbers, expressed either simply in decimal or often in the same octet-based dot-decimal notation used for IPv4 addresses.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] By convention, area 0 (zero), or 0.0.0.0, represents the *core* or *backbone* area of an OSPF network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] While the identifications of other areas may be chosen at will, administrators often select the IP address of a main router in an area as the area identifier.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each additional area must have a connection to the OSPF backbone area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Such connections are maintained by an interconnecting router, known as an area border router (ABR).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An ABR maintains separate link-state databases for each area it serves and maintains summarized routes for all areas in the network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF runs over IPv4 and IPv6, but does not use a transport protocol such as UDP or TCP.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It encapsulates its data directly in IP packets with protocol number 89.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This is in contrast to other routing protocols, such as the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF implements its own transport error detection and correction functions.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF also uses multicast addressing for distributing route information within a broadcast domain.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It reserves the multicast addresses *224.0.0.5* (IPv4) and *ff02::5* (IPv6) for all SPF/link state routers (AllSPFRouters) and *224.0.0.6* (IPv4) and *ff02::6* (IPv6) for all Designated Routers (AllDRouters).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For non-broadcast networks, special provisions for configuration facilitate neighbor discovery.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF multicast IP packets never traverse IP routers, they never travel more than one hop.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The protocol may therefore be considered a link-layer protocol, but is often also attributed to the application layer in the TCP/IP model.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It has a virtual link feature that can be used to create an adjacency tunnel across multiple hops.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF over IPv4 can operate securely between routers, optionally using a variety of authentication methods to allow only trusted routers to participate in routing.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPFv3 (IPv6) relies on standard IPv6 protocol security (IPsec), and has no internal authentication methods.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For routing IP multicast traffic, OSPF supports the Multicast Open Shortest Path First (MOSPF) protocol.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Cisco does not include MOSPF in their OSPF implementations.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Protocol Independent Multicast (PIM) in conjunction with OSPF or other IGPs, is widely deployed.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF version 3 introduces modifications to the IPv4 implementation of the protocol.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Except for virtual links, all neighbor exchanges use IPv6 link-local addressing exclusively.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The IPv6 protocol runs per link, rather than based on the subnet.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All IP prefix information has been removed from the link-state advertisements and from the *hello* discovery packet, making OSPFv3 essentially protocol-independent.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Despite the expanded IP addressing to 128 bits in IPv6, area and router Identifications are still based on 32-bit numbers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF supports complex networks with multiple routers, including backup routers, to balance traffic load on multiple links to other subnets.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Neighboring routers in the same broadcast domain or at each end of a point-to-point link communicate with each other via the OSPF protocol.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Routers form *adjacencies* when they have detected each other.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This detection is initiated when a router identifies itself in a *hello* protocol packet.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Upon acknowledgment, this establishes a *two-way state* and the most basic relationship.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The routers in an Ethernet or Frame Relay network select a *designated router* (DR) and a *backup designated router* (BDR), which act as a hub to reduce traffic between routers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF uses both unicast and multicast transmission modes to send "hello" packets and link-state updates.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] As a link-state routing protocol, OSPF establishes and maintains neighbor relationships for exchanging routing updates with other routers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The neighbor relationship table is called an *adjacency database*.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two OSPF routers are neighbors if they are members of the same subnet and share the same area ID, subnet mask, timers and authentication.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In essence, OSPF neighborship is a relationship between two routers that allows them to see and understand each other but nothing more.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF neighbors do not exchange any routing information – the only packets they exchange are hello packets.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF adjacencies are formed between selected neighbors and allow them to exchange routing information.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two routers must first be neighbors, and only then can they become adjacent.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two routers become adjacent if at least one of them is designated router or backup designated router (on multiaccess-type networks), or they are interconnected by a point-to-point or point-to-multipoint network type.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For forming a neighbor relationship between the interfaces, the relationship must be in the same OSPF area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] While an interface may be configured to belong to multiple areas, this is generally not practiced.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When configured in a second area, an interface must be configured as a secondary interface.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Virtual link over Virtual links, tunneling and sham links, are a form of connections that goes over the routing engine, and is not a direct connection to the remote host.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each OSPF router within a network communicates with other neighboring routers on each connecting interface to establish the states of all adjacencies.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Every such communication sequence is a separate *conversation* identified by the pair of router IDs of the communicating neighbors.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] RFC 2328 specifies the protocol for initiating these conversations (*Hello Protocol*) and for establishing full adjacencies (*database description packets*, *link-state request packets*).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Attempt: The *attempt* state is similar to the *down* state, except that a router is in the process of efforts to establish a conversation with another router, but is only used on non-broadcast multiple-access networks (NBMAs).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Init: The *init* state indicates that a hello packet has been received from a neighbor, but the router has not established a two-way conversation.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two-way: The *two-way* state indicates the establishment of a bidirectional conversation between two routers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This state immediately precedes the establishment of adjacency.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This is the lowest state of a router that may be considered as a DR.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Exchange: In the *exchange* state, a router is sending its link-state database information to the adjacent neighbor.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] At this state, a router can exchange all OSPF routing protocol packets.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Loading: In the *loading* state, a router requests the most recent link-state advertisements (LSAs) from its neighbor discovered in the previous state.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Full: The *full* state concludes the conversation when the routers are fully adjacent, and the state appears in all router- and network-LSAs.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The link-state databases of the neighbors are fully synchronized.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In broadcast multiple-access networks, neighbor adjacency is formed dynamically using multicast hello packets to *224.0.0.5*.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A network where OSPF advertises the network, but OSPF will not start neighbor adjacency.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In a non-broadcast multiple-access (NBMA) network, a neighbor adjacency is formed by sending unicast packets to another router.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A non-broadcast network can have more than two routers, but broadcast is not supported.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A network is divided into OSPF *areas* that are logical groupings of contiguous hosts and networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An area includes its connecting router, having an interface for each connected network link.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each router maintains a separate link-state database for the area whose information may be summarized towards the rest of the network by the connecting router.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Thus, the topology of an area is unknown outside the area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This reduces the routing traffic between parts of an autonomous system.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Though OSPF can handle thousands of routers, there is a concern reaching the capacity of the forwarding information base (FIB) table when the network contains lots of routes and lower-end devices.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Modern low-end routers have a full gigabyte of RAM, which allows them to handle many routers in an area 0.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Many resources refer to OSPF guides from over 20 years ago, where it was impressive to have 64 MB of RAM.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Areas are uniquely identified with 32-bit numbers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The area identifiers are commonly written in the dot-decimal notation, familiar from IPv4 addressing.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] However, they are not IP addresses and may duplicate, without conflict, any IPv4 address.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The area identifiers for IPv6 implementations (OSPFv3) also use 32-bit identifiers written in the same notation.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When dotted formatting is omitted, most implementations expand area *1* to the area identifier *0.0.0.1*, but some have been known to expand it as *1.0.0.0*.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Several vendors (Cisco, Allied Telesis, Juniper, Alcatel-Lucent, Huawei, Quagga), implement *totally stubby* and *NSSA totally stubby area* for stub and not-so-stubby areas.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Although not covered by RFC standards, they are considered by many to be standard features in OSPF implementations.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The backbone area (also known as *area 0* or *area 0.0.0.0*) forms the core of an OSPF network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All other areas are connected to it, either directly or through other routers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF requires this to prevent routing loops.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Inter-area routing happens via routers connected to the backbone area and to their own associated areas.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It is the logical and physical structure for the 'OSPF domain' and is attached to all nonzero areas in the OSPF domain.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In OSPF the term *autonomous system boundary router* (ASBR) is historic, in the sense that many OSPF domains can coexist in the same Internet-visible autonomous system, RFC 1996.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All OSPF areas must connect to the backbone area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This connection, however, can be through a virtual link.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For example, assume area 0.0.0.1 has a physical connection to area 0.0.0.0.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Further assume that area 0.0.0.2 has no direct connection to the backbone, but this area does have a connection to area 0.0.0.1.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Area 0.0.0.2 can use a virtual link through the *transit area* 0.0.0.1 to reach the backbone.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] To be a transit area, an area has to have the transit attribute, so it cannot be stubby in any way.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A regular area is just a non-backbone (nonzero) area without a specific feature, generating and receiving summary and external LSAs.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The backbone area is a special type of such area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A stub area is an area that does not receive route advertisements external to the AS, and routing from within the area is based entirely on a default route.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An ABR deletes type 4 and 5 LSAs from internal routers, sends them a default route of 0.0.0.0, and turns itself into a default gateway.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This reduces LSDB and routing table size for internal routers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Modifications to the basic concept of stub area have been implemented by systems vendors, such as the *totally stubby area* (TSA) and the *not-so-stubby area* (NSSA), both extensions in Cisco Systems routing equipment.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *totally stubby area* is similar to a stub area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] However, this area does not allow *summary* routes in addition to not having *external* routes; that is, *inter-area* (IA) routes are not summarized into totally stubby areas.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The only way for traffic to get routed outside the area is a default route, which is the only Type-3 LSA advertised into the area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When there is only one route out of the area, fewer routing decisions have to be made by the route processor, which lowers system resource utilization.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Occasionally, it is said that a TSA can have only one ABR.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *not-so-stubby area* (NSSA) is a type of stub area that can import autonomous system external routes and send them to other areas, but still cannot receive AS-external routes from other areas.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] NSSA is an extension of the stub area feature that allows the injection of external routes in a limited fashion into the stub area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A case study simulates an NSSA getting around the stub-area problem of not being able to import external addresses.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It visualizes the following activities: the ASBR imports external addresses with a type 7 LSA, the ABR converts a type 7 LSA to type 5 and floods it to other areas, the ABR acts as an ASBR for other areas.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The ASBRs do not take type 5 LSAs and then convert to type 7 LSAs for the area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An addition to the standard functionality of an NSSA, the *totally stubby NSSA* is an NSSA that takes on the attributes of a TSA, meaning that type 3 and 4 summary routes are not flooded into this type of area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Redistribution into an NSSA area creates a special type of LSA known as type 7, which can exist only in an NSSA area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An NSSA ASBR generates this LSA, and an NSSA ABR router translates it into a type 5 LSA, which gets propagated into the OSPF domain.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A newly acquired subsidiary is one example of where it might be suitable for an area to be simultaneously not-so-stubby and totally stubby if the practical place to put an ASBR is on the edge of a totally stubby area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In such a case, the ASBR does send externals into the totally stubby area, and they are available to OSPF speakers within that area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In Cisco's implementation, the external routes can be summarized before injecting them into the totally stubby area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In general, the ASBR should not advertise default into the TSA-NSSA, although this can work with extremely careful design and operation, for the limited special cases in which such an advertisement makes sense.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] By declaring the totally stubby area as NSSA, no external routes from the backbone, except the default route, enter the area being discussed.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The externals do reach area 0.0.0.0 via the TSA-NSSA, but no routes other than the default route enter the TSA-NSSA.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Routers in the TSA-NSSA send all traffic to the ABR, except to routes advertised by the ASBR.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] has all its interfaces belonging to the same area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] is a router that connects one or more areas to the main backbone network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It is considered a member of all areas it is connected to.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] of the link-state database in memory, one for each area to which that router is connected.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Backbone routers may also be area border routers, but do not have to be.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] is a router that is connected by using more than one routing protocol and that exchanges routing information with routers autonomous systems.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] received from other, external ASs throughout its own autonomous system.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An ASBR creates External LSAs for external addresses and floods them to all areas via ABR.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Routers in other areas use ABRs as next hops to access external addresses.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Then ABRs forward packets to the ASBR that announces the external addresses.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The router type is an attribute of an OSPF process.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A given physical router may have one or more OSPF processes.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For example, a router that is connected to more than one area, and which receives routes from a BGP process connected to another AS, is both an area border router and an autonomous system boundary router.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each router has an identifier, customarily written in the dotted-decimal format (e.g., 1.2.3.4) of an IP address.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This identifier must be established in every OSPF instance.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If not explicitly configured, the highest logical IP address will be duplicated as the router identifier.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] However, since the router identifier is not an IP address, it does not have to be a part of any routable subnet in the network, and often isn't to avoid confusion.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A system of *designated router* (DR) and *backup designated router* (BDR), is used to reduce network traffic by providing a source for routing updates.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The DR and BDR maintains a complete topology table of the network and sends the updates to the other routers via multicast.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All routers in a multi-access network segment will form a leader/follower relationship with the DR and BDR.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] They will form adjacencies with the DR and BDR only.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Every time a router sends an update, it sends it to the DR and BDR on the multicast address *224.0.0.6*.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The DR will then send the update out to all other routers in the area, to the multicast address *224.0.0.5*.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This way all the routers do not have to constantly update each other, and can rather get all their updates from a single source.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The use of multicasting further reduces the network load.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DRs and BDRs are always setup/elected on OSPF broadcast networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DR's can also be elected on NBMA (Non-Broadcast Multi-Access) networks such as Frame Relay or ATM.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DRs or BDRs are not elected on point-to-point links (such as a point-to-point WAN connection) because the two routers on either side of the link must become fully adjacent and the bandwidth between them cannot be further optimized.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DR and non-DR routers evolve from 2-way to full adjacency relationships by exchanging DD, Request, and Update.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *designated router* (DR) is the router interface elected among all routers on a particular multiaccess network segment, generally assumed to be broadcast multiaccess.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Special techniques, often vendor-dependent, may be needed to support the DR function on non-broadcast multiaccess (NBMA) media.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It is usually wise to configure the individual virtual circuits of an NBMA subnet as individual point-to-point lines; the techniques used are implementation-dependent.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *backup designated router* (BDR) is a router that becomes the designated router if the current designated router has a problem or fails.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The BDR is the OSPF router with the second-highest priority at the time of the last election.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A given router can have some interfaces that are designated (DR) and others that are backup designated (BDR), and others that are non-designated.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If no router is a DR or a BDR on a given subnet, the BDR is first elected, and then a second election is held for the DR.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A router that has not been selected to be *designated router* (DR) or *backup designated router* (BDR).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The router forms an adjacency to both the *designated router* (DR) and the *backup designated router* (BDR).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For other non (B)DR, the adjacency stops at *2-ways* State.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Unlike other routing protocols, OSPF does not carry data via a transport protocol, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) or the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Instead, OSPF forms IP datagrams directly, packaging them using protocol number 89 for the IP Protocol field.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF defines five different message types, for various types of communication.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF's Hello messages are used as a form of greeting, to allow a router to discover other adjacent routers on its local links and networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The messages establish relationships between neighboring devices (called adjacencies) and communicate key parameters about how OSPF is to be used in the autonomous system or area.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] During normal operation, routers send hello messages to their neighbors at regular intervals (the *hello interval*); if a router stops receiving hello messages from a neighbor, after a set period (the *dead interval*) the router will assume the neighbor has gone down.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] messages are used by one router to request updated information about a portion of the LSDB from another router.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The message specifies the link(s) for which the requesting device wants more current information.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] messages contain updated information about the state of certain links on the LSDB.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] They are sent in response to a link state request message, and also broadcast or multicast by routers on a regular basis.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Their contents are used to update the information in the LSDBs of routers that receive them.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] messages provide reliability to the link-state exchange process, by explicitly acknowledging receipt of a Link State Update message.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF uses *path cost* as its basic routing metric, which was defined by the standard not to equate to any standard value such as speed, so the network designer could pick a metric important to the design.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In practice, it is determined by comparing the speed of the interface to a reference-bandwidth for the OSPF process.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The cost is determined by dividing the reference bandwidth by the interface speed (although the cost for any interface can be manually overridden).
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Here is an example table that shows the routing metric or 'cost calculation' on an interface.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If a layer 2 switch is between the two devices running OSPF, one side may negotiate a speed different from the other side.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This can create an asymmetric routing on the link (Router 1 to Router 2 could cost '1' and the return path could cost '10'), which may lead to unintended consequences.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Metrics, however, are only directly comparable when of the same type.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Despite the expansion of addresses to 128 bits in IPv6, area and router identifications are still 32-bit numbers.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A customer can use OSPF over a MPLS VPN, where the service provider uses BGP or RIP as their interior gateway protocol.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When using OSPF over MPLS VPN, the VPN backbone becomes part of the OSPF backbone area 0.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In all areas, isolated copies of the IGP are run.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] To achieve this, a modified OSPF-BGP redistribution is used.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All OSPF routes retain the source LSA type and metric.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] To prevent loops, an optional DN bit is set by the service provider in LSAs from the provider equipment to indicate that a route has already been sent to the customer's equipment.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF-TE is an extension to OSPF, extending the expressivity to allow for traffic engineering and use on non-IP networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Using OSPF-TE, more information about the topology can be exchanged using opaque LSA carrying type–length–value elements.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] These extensions allow OSPF-TE to run completely out of band of the data plane network.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This means that it can also be used on non-IP networks, such as optical networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF-TE is used in GMPLS networks as a means to describe the topology over which GMPLS paths can be established.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] GMPLS uses its own path setup and forwarding protocols once it has the full network map.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP), OSPF-TE is used for recording and flooding RSVP signaled bandwidth reservations for label-switched paths within the link-state database.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] RFC 3717 documents work in optical routing for IP based on extensions to OSPF and IS-IS.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The Multicast Open Shortest Path First (MOSPF) protocol is an extension to OSPF to support multicast routing.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] MOSPF allows routers to share information about group memberships.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF is a widely deployed routing protocol that can converge a network in a few seconds and guarantee loop-free paths.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It has many features that allow the imposition of policies about the propagation of routes that may be appropriate to keep local, for load sharing, and for selective route importing.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] IS-IS, in contrast, can be tuned for lower overhead in a stable network, the sort more common in ISP than enterprise networks.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] There are some historical accidents that made IS-IS the preferred IGP for ISPs, but ISPs today may well choose to use the features of the now-efficient implementations of OSPF, after first considering the pros and cons of IS-IS in service provider environments.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF can provide better load-sharing on external links than other IGPs.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When the default route to an ISP is injected into OSPF from multiple ASBRs as a Type I external route and the same external cost specified, other routers will go to the ASBR with the least path cost from its location.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This can be tuned further by adjusting the external cost.
[src:is-is-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If the default route from different ISPs is injected with different external costs, as a Type II external route, the lower-cost default becomes the primary exit and the higher-cost becomes the backup only.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] A **routing protocol** specifies how routers communicate with each other to distribute information that enables them to select paths between nodes on a computer network.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Routers perform the traffic directing functions on the Internet; data packets are forwarded through the networks of the internet from router to router until they reach their destination computer.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Routing algorithms determine the specific choice of route.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Each router has a prior knowledge only of networks attached to it directly.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] A routing protocol shares this information first among immediate neighbors, and then throughout the network.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] This way, routers gain knowledge of the topology of the network.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] The ability of routing protocols to dynamically adjust to changing conditions such as disabled connections and components and route data around obstructions is what gives the Internet its fault tolerance and high availability.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Certain additional characteristics such as multilayer interfacing may also be employed as a means of distributing uncompromised networking gateways to authorized ports.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] This has the added benefit of preventing issues with routing protocol loops.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Many routing protocols are defined in technical standards documents called RFCs.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Interior gateway protocols (IGPs) exchange routing information within a single routing domain.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Exterior gateway protocols exchange routing information between autonomous systems.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Many software implementations exist for most of the common routing protocols.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Examples of open-source applications are Bird Internet routing daemon, Quagga, GNU Zebra, OpenBGPD, OpenOSPFD, and XORP.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Some network certification courses distinguish between routing protocols and *routed* protocols.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] A **routed protocol** is used to deliver application traffic.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] It provides appropriate addressing information in its internet layer or network layer to allow a packet to be forwarded from one network to another.
[src:is-is-routing/routing-protocol] Examples of routed protocols are the Internet Protocol (IP) and Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
